    <h2>Macy's Favorite Things</h2>
    <body>
        Macy loves anything happy and colorful. She is a creature of the sunshine and loves being outside. Especially if hiking or water are involved. Macy spent part of her childhood in Hawaii and loves the ocean and anything that has anything to do with water. Being a competitive swimmer her whole life also contributed to this love of water. Traveling is another hobby of Macy's. She has been to over twenty countries around the world and loves learning about different cultures and places around the world. Another thing that Macy loves is board games. She is undefeated in "Ticket to Ride" and plays "Catan" with her friends every week.
    </body>
    <h2>A Brief History of Macy</h2>
    <body>
        Macy was born to a military family in Georgia. Before going to college, Macy had moved about 14 times. She mostly lived in random states in America, but the funnest places she lived were Germany and Hawaii. She did many sports as a child, but her favorites were trampoline tumbling, trampoline gymnastics, and swim team. Swim team eventually became her life and she spent hours in the pool every day of her teenage years. After graduating high school, Macy went to a year of college at Utah Tech University, studying mechanical engineering. Then, she served a mission for the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in Tokyo, Japan for 18 months. She returned from Japan in March of last year and began studying at BYU in August. After taking Physics 121, and realizing she had a soul-wrenching fear of taking the Statics class for mechanical engineering, she realized that mechanical engineering was not the route for her to take in life and she switched her major to Cybersecurity. Yay! Another important aspect of Macy's life is work. She worked as an admin assisstant at a solar panel company before her mission and currently works as a software engineering consultant. Which, she loves. Life is great.
    </body>
    <h2>A Favorite Memory</h2>
    <body>
        When Macy finished her freshman year of college, her and her two best friends loaded up her truck and went camping in Bryce Canyon National Park. It was truly one of the most amazing moments of her life. Bryce Canyon is incredible. When they pulled up to the park entrance, it was later in the afternoon and the ranger told them that she only had one camping spot left, and she gave it to them. Which was perfect because otherwise they would have been setting up camp on the side of the road somewhere random. A little less fun. The next two days were filled with some of the most gorgeous and fun hikes this world has to offer. And, this was in early May, so there were small amounts of snow atop the red rock but that melted during the next day. On the drive back to St. George, they stopped at some sand dunes and that was also a core memory.
